reviews.review_text:
In the top 3 of 1984 37 years, and a day ago. Wow! This 24 bit audience is a  sublime show and was  team effort by Bill Koucky, Scott Clugston and Charlie Miller. I was in attendance this night on the GA floor and it may have been in the  top three of the year.

A killer Stranger opens the show and the band is completely dialed in. TLEO is classic early '80's fare with Brent really stepping it up.
Time to kick back with a  sweet and groovy CC. Rider, as is  usual Bobby gets very naughty with the classic off the rails slide solo.
You know Jerry is in great spirits when B.E. Women is his second song and this one is text book perfect, with that extra fast tempo which was always my preference.

Brother Esau always got off to  an off balanced start and this one is no different, but they quickly  regroup and you get an amazing version with plenty of Phil in the mix.

The good times continue down below the Mason Dixon line with an outstanding version of Tennessee Jed, with Jerry's voice strong and clear. Phil comes in nice and robust during Jerry's ending solo with reaches an orgasmic peak.

One wonderful characteristic of this set is that it doesn't feel rushed and the  pace is nice and organic.
Then it makes perfect sense to begin Let it Grow to end the set. The  band again is really listening to each other and Jerry is simply on top of his  game, his extended solo to the first bridge is quite breath taking.
Bobby's tone  this year was starting to get alittle dirty but it still sounds sweet. Brent  helps really pushes this one to some amazing moments, there is one slight hiccup at the 8:36 mark but the recovery  is quite good so you be the  judge. This  Let it Grow ends up  being a very noteworthy  version in the big  picture of the 1980's.

Now to the meat of the show. Set II.
They open with a strong Touch, which  still has that extra power that was a hallmark of the  early '80 versions.

Then a  extremely wonderful PITB. It is only 8 minutes  long but don't let that fool you, as there is plenty of amazing details and nuances that the band dance through with ease and then Jerry arrives at Terrapin Station and what an  amazing version it is. Jerry just dominates on this one, as he has all night long. Brent and Bobby stay on stage and break into  Don't Need Love, which was kinda a  shock when I hear it this  night as the lyrics are quite  candid, but ove rthe years I have  grown to love this song and Brent really puts his heart out on this one.

Drumz is amazing and on this outstanding, I mean REALLY outstanding, audience recording they sound even better and Mickey plays some nice beam, which was a hallmark of these mid '80 shows, so sonically this one gets quite wild.

Space is  nice and nothing to crazy, but is quite pleasant and enjoyable to listen to...then to drop into Morning Dew! What a wonderful and sublime transition and one sadly that only lasted a for  few more shows this year before they would never place this song in that spot again. I would highly recommend checking out the one from 7/22/84, which is the cat's meow and the last one they ever played out of space.

But let's back up here kids. This  Dew is everything you want it to be. Strong and passionate vocals from Jerry, plenty of Phil, great ensemble playing by everyone else and and a wonderful  joyous peak to close it out. Healy had a little echo on Jerry's voice at the end and actually works out quite nicely. Jerry begins the end  jam  by mainly playing power chords but then make that killer transition at the 10:42 mark and then he cranks it  up.

A  perfect climax.

Throwing Stones may  be the only weak link the entire night, as it is  good but nothing over the  top but then they  go old school by dropping into Saturday night, which was a nice change. They actually did this several more times throughout this year, such as  very good T-Stones> Stella Blue on 10/9/84.

Then a  breathtaking and poignant Baby Blue, these mid '80's version were simply some of the best the band ever played and Jerry is golden on it.

Yup this night in Hampton was a Jerry show,

Happy trails.
